  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "6/6 vision, often referred to as 20/20 vision in the US, is considered normal vision. If someone has 6/6 myopia, it means they have nearsightedness (myopia) and their vision is corrected to 6/6 (or 20/20) with glasses or contact lenses.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **6/6 (or 20/20) vision:** This is a standard measure of visual acuity. It means that at 6 meters (or 20 feet in the US), you can see what a person with normal vision should be able to see at that distance. It doesn't mean your vision is perfect, just that you have normal visual acuity.\n\n*   **Myopia (Nearsightedness):** This means you can see objects clearly up close, but distant objects appear blurry. This is because the eye focuses light in front of the retina instead of directly on it.\n\nTherefore, having \"6/6 myopia\" means:\n\n*   Without corrective lenses (glasses or contacts), you have myopia and distant objects are blurry.\n*   With corrective lenses, your vision is corrected to 6/6 (or 20/20), and you can see clearly at a distance.\n\nIn short, it means you need glasses or contacts for distance vision, but with them, you see normally.\n",
